Adversarial Questions And Answers
Q: Did you just make CI faster by running fewer tests?
No. The goal was to preserve the same unit test scope, not reduce coverage. Integration specs were excluded because they belonged to a separate integration stage and were not the slow part I was trying to fix. I also preserved backtrace and profile behavior from the old command.

Q: Why did you use parallel_tests instead of building your own splitter?
Because splitting RSpec files, coordinating Rails test databases, and handling worker-specific environment variables are already solved problems. A maintained gem reduced custom code and lowered maintenance risk.

Q: Why did the database config need to change?
Parallel workers cannot safely share one test database. parallel_tests sets TEST_ENV_NUMBER, so the database name used that value. Each worker got its own test database, which reduced cross-process interference.

Q: Why was 8 workers not the best number if Jenkins had 8 CPUs?
Because the test suite was not purely CPU-bound. Rails tests also use database setup, Rails boot, file loading, Docker resources, disk I/O, logs, memory, and instrumentation. At higher worker counts, those shared resources can become bottlenecks. In testing, 4 workers gave better throughput than 8.

Q: Did you know exactly why performance degraded after 4 workers?
Not with complete certainty. The evidence showed that 4 was the best measured point. The likely causes were database contention, Rails boot overhead, memory pressure, disk I/O, Docker overhead, Datadog instrumentation overhead, or uneven shard distribution. I would rather say what I measured and what I suspected than claim a root cause I did not prove.

Q: Why not spend more time proving the exact cause?
The goal was to reduce CI feedback time safely. Once 4 workers gave a strong improvement and the suite was stable, deeper profiling became a follow-up optimization. I would still monitor shard duration, DB load, and CI resource usage after rollout.

Q: What problems did parallel execution expose?
It exposed hidden load-order dependencies. Some specs passed in serial because another spec had already loaded certain Rails classes. When the suite was split across workers, that ordering disappeared. The fix was to eager load the Rails app in the test environment through rails_helper.

Q: Why not eager load only inside the failing specs?
That was one option, and I considered it. But if the real problem was that workers started with different loaded state, fixing individual specs would be narrow and fragile. Moving eager loading to rails_helper made the test environment consistent for all workers.

Q: Did eager loading reduce the performance benefit?
It probably added some boot cost, but it made the suite deterministic. A fast flaky test stage is not useful. The measured runtime was still much better than the original serial run.

Q: How did you make sure Datadog visibility was not lost?
I added the parallel test command through Drake and preserved Datadog environment variables such as branch, commit SHA, repository URL, author, commit message, and tags. Datadog was mainly for CI/test visibility, not for making the tests pass. I also verified a sample run showed up in Datadog.

Q: Why did you not parallelize integration tests too?
Because integration tests were not the bottleneck. The unit stage was taking around 20 minutes, so that was the high-impact target. Parallelizing integration tests would have added risk without much payoff.

Q: What did review improve in the PR?
Review caught important production details: excluding integration specs correctly, keeping profiler and backtrace behavior, preserving Datadog CI metrics, explaining TEST_ENV_NUMBER, and moving eager loading to the right helper.

Q: What would you improve next?
I would track shard timings and use historical runtime data to balance workers better. I would also monitor database load and CI resource usage to understand exactly why performance flattened after 4 workers.

Q: What is the main engineering lesson?
Parallelism is not automatically faster. You have to measure the real system. The best solution was not "use all CPUs." The best solution was the fastest stable configuration that preserved correctness and observability.
